# General rule: text is normalised to LF on commit AND on checkout, on every
# platform (deterministic regardless of core.autocrlf). The committed lockfile
# test asserts LF line endings, and `git archive` / a fresh clone must reproduce
# them byte-for-byte.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Binary assets: never apply text or EOL filters.
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.pdf binary
*.xlsx binary
*.xls binary

# EXCEPTION (later rules win over earlier ones):
# raw/ is the system's citation base: the bytes on disk are the truth
# (source_hash = md5 of the bytes; [VERIFIED] citations resolve to physical
# line numbers). No EOL conversion, ever: a checkout must reproduce the
# original SAP export byte-for-byte.
raw/** -text

# Git hooks are sh scripts: they must stay LF even on Windows (a CRLF in the
# shebang makes execution fail with `/bin/sh^M`). Force eol=lf on checkout.
core/githooks/** text eol=lf
